{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":676,"record_hash":"sha256:6e77c5f74d55deeed3511e404b16afa35e6c7abe50be1540d0e2d5aba7083684","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:47:08.628Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Lane 3 Verdict**\\n\\nUse **out-of-process service** for production. Use **NAPI-RS only if Forge is confirmed to run as a stateful Node/container backend** with writable disk, `git`, native addon loading, and enough request/worker time.\\n\\nNAPI is the cleanest *Rust-to-Node API*, but it does not solve the real hard part: Agent Trail needs local Git/GitMeta state on disk.\\n\\n| Option | Fit | Notes |\\n|---|---:|---|\\n| **NAPI-RS / N-API addon** | Good only in stateful Forge | Clean TS API, async support, ABI-stable Node addon story. But native `.node` packaging + Next bundling need care. Runs inside the Next process. |\\n| **Helper binary** | Good prototype / fallback | Easier process isolation. JSON over stdin/stdout or args. Still needs binary packaging, filesystem, `git`, and durable cache. |\\n| **WASM/WASI** | Bad fit | Node WASI is still experimental, Rust WASI cannot spawn processes on base `wasm32-wasip1`, and our path likely needs real Git repo access. Nope. |\\n| **Separate service** | Best | Owns repo cache, locks, git binary, queueing, cleanup, platform choice. Forge stays thin and compartmentalized. |\\n\\n**NAPI-RS Findings**\\n\\nN-API is ABI-stable across Node versions, which is the right native-addon foundation: [Node-API ABI stability](https://nodejs.org/api/n-api.html), [Node ABI stability](https://nodejs.org/learn/modules/abi-stability).\\n\\nNAPI-RS supports Rust `cdylib` addons, generated `.node` binaries, and async functions: [napi crate docs](https://docs.rs/crate/napi/latest), [NAPI-RS CLI](https://napi-rs.github.io/napi-rs/cli/). The CLI can emit platform-suffixed artifacts like `index.darwin-x64.node` and build target triples.\\n\\nNext.js bundles server dependencies by default, so native packages should be externalized with `serverExternalPackages`: [Next serverExternalPackages](https://nextjs.[REDACTED:entropy]). Routes must stay on Node runtime, not Edge: [Next route runtime](https://nextjs.[REDACTED:entropy]).\\n\\nRisk: the addon lives in the Next process. A Rust panic may be manageable; a segfault is not. Also, Linux `glibc`/`musl`, arch, and deployment image must match the shipped artifact.\\n\\n**Helper Binary Findings**\\n\\nNode’s `child_process.spawn` is stable and gives process isolation: [Node child_process](https://nodejs.org/api/child_process.html). npm can expose binaries via `package.json#bin`, and platform packages can use `os`, `cpu`, `libc`, and `optionalDependencies`: [npm package.json](https://docs.npmjs.[REDACTED:entropy]).\\n\\nThis is less elegant than NAPI but operationally sturdy. It also avoids native addon bundling weirdness. Bad if the API becomes chatty; fine if the backend sends one request and gets one JSON response.\\n\\n**WASM/WASI Findings**\\n\\nBad match. Node’s WASI module is experimental and warns not to rely on it as a secure FS sandbox: [Node WASI](https://nodejs.org/api/wasi.html). Rust’s `wasm32-wasip1` supports some filesystem operations, but process spawning always errors: [Rust wasm32-wasip1](https://doc.rust-lang.[REDACTED:entropy].html). Agent Trail wants real Git repo behavior; WASM turns that into yak hair.\\n\\n**Service Findings**\\n\\nThis is the architecture I’d pick. Forge exposes the API/UI and calls an Agent Trail generator service. The service can be Rust-native, with no Rust-to-Node bridge at all. It owns:\\n\\n- local bare/non-bare repo cache\\n- GitMeta SQLite/materialization\\n- `git` availability\\n- per-repo locking\\n- cleanup/quotas\\n- retries/background jobs\\n- native platform concerns\\n\\nIf Forge is on Vercel/serverless, this becomes basically mandatory. Vercel functions have bundle, duration, and filesystem constraints, and their docs recommend object storage for persistence: [Vercel files in functions](https://vercel.[REDACTED:entropy]), [Vercel function limits](https://vercel.com/docs/functions/limitations).\\n\\n**Recommendation**\\n\\nBuild **Agent Trail generator as a separate Rust service**. Keep Forge as API façade + web UI.\\n\\nIf we later prove Forge deploys as a long-lived container with writable persistent cache, then a dedicated **NAPI-RS package** is the cleanest in-repo integration. Helper binary is the pragmatic fallback if Next/native packaging gets annoying. WASM should be off the table.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:47:08.628Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}